In order to unambiguously elucidate their structures by NMR experiments, the ethanol extract was purified by size exclusion chromatography, followed by further purification steps by reversed-phase HPLC-RI, to obtain sixteen compounds. Their structures were established by 1D and 2D-NMR experiments along with ESIMS and HRESIMS analysis (
Fig. 2
).

A detailed analysis of NMR data of compounds 8 ,
10 — 12
, and 14 showed the presence of a common moiety. For compound 8 , the 1 H NMR spectrum showed an aromatic signal at d 7.10 (2H, s), ascribable to a galloyl moiety as confirmed by the HMBC correlation between the proton signal at d 7.10 with the carbon resonances at d 121.1 (C-1
00
), 146.4 (C-3
00
and C-5
00
), 139.5 (C-4
00
) and 167.9 (C-7
00
) ( Table 2 ). Moreover, for the sugar unit an anomeric signal at d 4.89 (d, J ¼ 7.8 Hz) was evident. On the basis of HSQC, HMBC, COSY and 1D-TOCSY experiments a b -glucopyranosyl unit was identified. The absolute configuration of the sugar unit was determined by acid hydrolysis of compound 8 and was assigned as D-glucose on the basis of its optical rotation value ( Horo et al., 2015 ). The downfield shifts of protons at d 4.60 and 4.43 (H 2 -6
0
) of the primary alcoholic function of glucose and their HMBC correlation with the carbon resonance at d 167.9 (C-7
00
) revealed the site of esterification. The b - D-glucopyranosyl-(6- O -galloyl)-unit was also identified in the NMR spectra of compounds
10 — 12
and 14 .

